		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_38104">
			
			Here's <br />
<a href="http://miwi.bsdcrew.de/2009/06/freebsd-80-install-with-a-usb-stick/" target="_blank">how-to</a> from miwi.bsdcrew.de. You've missed some steps:<br />
<br />
1: clear your stick:<br />
    <code style="background-color: #dee3e7; padding: .2px; margin: .1em; width: 99%; display: inline-block;"><samp></samp> <kbd>dd if=/dev/zero of=/dev/da0 bs=1k count=1</kbd></code><br />
2: make the USB-Stick bootable<br />
    <code style="background-color: #dee3e7; padding: .2px; margin: .1em; width: 99%; display: inline-block;"><samp></samp> <kbd>bsdlabel -Bw da0 auto</kbd></code><br />
3: create an UFS2 Filesystem with GEOM Lable “FreeBSD”<br />
    <code style="background-color: #dee3e7; padding: .2px; margin: .1em; width: 99%; display: inline-block;"><samp></samp> <kbd>newfs -L FreeBSD /dev/da0a</kbd></code><br />
<br />
I really don't know if these commands are available in OSX shell. But there's a chance because OSX open-source project Darwin is very closely related to BSD (Darwin is a BSD-derivate).
		</div>
		<!-- / message -->

		

		
		

		

		

		

